<DOC><DOCNO> AP881117-0254 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 0046EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   11-17 0559</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0584</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A British securities fraud probe that suggestsIvan Boesky duped Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. could give thetroubled firm a potent new attack on the credibility of theimprisoned insider trader.   Boesky has implicated Drexel in illegal acts and is expected tobe a star witness against the investment house.   Legal experts said Wednesday that the British investigation alsomay mean new trouble for Boesky if he did not disclose the allegedfraud against Drexel when he negotiated a plea-bargain agreement twoyears ago.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Michigan's request for federal protection fromCanadian automotive trade practices has been rejected by the U.S.trade representative.   Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter said Wednesday stateofficials had no right to file such a petition.   He also said the state's request had been superceded by afree-trade agreement negotiated between the United States andCanada. Under the program, Canada gives duty rebates on autos toforeign manufacturers in return for the use of Canadian parts intheir cars.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Treasury Department task force studying thesavings and loan crisis has concluded that taxpayer money must bespent to rescue the ailing system.   An administration official said Wednesday that the departmentalso is looking at a proposal to form a presidential board headed bythe Treasury secretary to oversee the bailout.   The official confirmed reports that the administration wasconsidering a plan to raise $20 billion to $30 billion a year forthree years.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A draft proposal to impose stricterrequirements for appealing government decisions to deny SocialSecurity, Medicare and welfare benefits has provoked a furor amongmembers of Congress and lobbyists for the elderly and disabled.   Chuck Kline, a spokesman for Dr. Otis R. Bowen, secretary ofhealth and human services, said Wednesday the proposed new ruleswere still under review within the Social Security Administrationand had not reached Bowen.   Several critics said the rules, if adopted, would violate the1935 Social Security Act and a 1971 Supreme Court ruling whichsupported an informal and liberal appeals process easily accessibleto the elderly, poor and disabled who frequently lack legal counsel.</TEXT><DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   More than $70 million worth of Douglas andnoble firs are being cut and bundled as Oregon growers readythemselves for the Christmas season.   With an expected harvest of 7.2 million trees this year, Oregonremains the nation's single largest supplier of Christmas trees.   Prices remain about the same as last year for premium trees, with6-foot to 7-foot Douglas firs bringing growers around $11, saidBryan Ostlund, spokesman for the Northwest Christmas TreeAssociation in Salem. Slower-growing noble firs bring a higherprice, he said, while retail prices are at least double what growersreceive.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The dollar plunged Wednesday as bearish sentiment overwhelmed thegovernment's report of a narrowing of the U.S. merchandise tradedeficit.   Bond prices declined sharply in response to the falling dollar.   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 38.59 to2,038.58, its lowest close since it stood at 2,002.31 on Sept. 1.   Crude futures prices fell; cocoa futures prices surged; silverfutures sagged while gold futures were little changed; copperfutures retreated; grains were lower; soybeans were higher; andlivestock and meat futures were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>